<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef493b6d8120a5e624de74b6b273ac25?s=50"></div><header><strong>viewWill/DidAppear and viewWill/DidDisappear should have &quot;animated&quot; argument label (Victor Gao)</strong> from <string>Victor Gao</string> &lt;victorgao44 at gmail.com&gt;<p>June 22, 2016 at 09:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>Hi all,<br></p><p>In the new iOS SDK with Swift 3, I noticed that the viewWillAppear, viewDidAppear, viewWillDisappear and viewDidDisappear hide the animated argument label. Which means when the SDK calls those methods it will look like this:<br></p><p>viewWillAppear(true)<br>viewDidAppear(true)<br>//and others<br></p><p>Obviously this runs counter to the Swift API Design Guidelines, thus results in unclear and confusing code. Instead, these methods should have the “animated&quot; argument label so it would be clear what the boolean flag means.<br></p><p>Cheers,<br>Victor Gao<br></p></div><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3488bcf34d8c45d917ed27d67a0ffa45?s=50"></div><header><strong>viewWill/DidAppear and viewWill/DidDisappear should have &quot;animated&quot; argument label (Victor Gao)</strong> from <string>David Hart</string> &lt;david at hartbit.com&gt;<p>June 22, 2016 at 05:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>I think you need to write a bug report on bugreport.apple.com as it concerns an Apple Framework. But yes, I agree with you :) It does not follow the Swift API Design Guidelines.<br></p><p>&gt; On 22 Jun 2016, at 14:38, Victor Gao via swift-evolution &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br>&gt; <br>&gt; Hi all,<br>&gt; <br>&gt; In the new iOS SDK with Swift 3, I noticed that the viewWillAppear, viewDidAppear, viewWillDisappear and viewDidDisappear hide the animated argument label. Which means when the SDK calls those methods it will look like this:<br>&gt; <br>&gt; viewWillAppear(true)<br>&gt; viewDidAppear(true)<br>&gt; //and others<br>&gt; <br>&gt; Obviously this runs counter to the Swift API Design Guidelines, thus results in unclear and confusing code. Instead, these methods should have the “animated&quot; argument label so it would be clear what the boolean flag means.<br>&gt; <br>&gt; Cheers,<br>&gt; Victor Gao<br>&gt; _______________________________________________<br>&gt; swift-evolution mailing list<br>&gt; swift-evolution at swift.org<br>&gt; https://lists.swift.org/mailman/listinfo/swift-evolution<br></p></div></li></ul></li></ul></div>    </main>
